  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Treatment of Acute Malnutrition in El Nino affected areas in Eastern Sudan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sudan has sustained high levels of acute malnutrition above the emergency threshold for at least three decades, and there are currently an estimated 550,000 children in need of treatment for severe acute malnutrition every year (Sudan National S3M 2013). On top of this situation, 2015 saw below-average rainfall resulting in a harvest that was 25% below the last 5-year average in part due to El Ni&#xF1;o-related dryness in eastern Sudan surplus-producing areas. Up to half of children with severe acute malnutrition will die without appropriate treatment (WHO SAM case-fatality estimation 30-50% (http://www.who.int/nutrition/topics/severe_malnutrition/en/index.html). Ready to Use Therapeutic food constitutes the major pillar in managing severe acute malnutrition and currently UNICEF is the only provider of RUTF to 14 of 18 states in Sudan. In the three Eastern States (Red Sea, Kassala and Gedaref), there are an estimated 72,343 children who suffer from severe acute malnutrition every year (Sudan S3M data 2013). This project aims to ensure a sustained and healthy RUTF core pipeline to increase access of needy children in highly vulnerable areas in Eastern Sudan that are particularly affected by the current drought that is caused by El Nino.</narrative>
  </description>
